        <body>
            
            <div type="bibliography">
                
                <p>Not included into <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/></bibl>;
                <bibl><ptr target="#cdl2020d"/><citedRange/></bibl>.</p>
            </div>
            
            
            <div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key="..."><name nymRef="Φερώι"/>Φερὼι</persName>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key="..."><name nymRef="Σεμηρ" type="patronymic">Σεμηρος</name></persName>
                </ab>
            </div>
            
            <div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
            </div>
            
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Pherô fille de Semer.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Phero daughter of Semer.</p>
		    </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
                <p>Pherò figlia di Semer.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div type="commentary">
                
                <p>The feminine name Phero is a short form of the numerous compounds in <foreign xml:lang="grc">Φερε/ο-</foreign>, amongst which <foreign xml:lang="grc">Φερονίκα</foreign> and 
                    <foreign xml:lang="grc">Φερενίκα</foreign> are of use in the region. Her father's name, only attested in Cyrenaica, belongs to the Libyan stock and is attested in the fourth and third centuries.</p>
                <p>Moreover, we know also a funerary base for a woman with the same name and same father's name (<ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr105700</ref>). It is impossible to guess whether the two monuments (and the two letterings) are 
                contemporaneous or should be separated by a span of time. The question of a possible relationship  is treated by the other authors of the publication with archaeological arguments.</p>
                <p/>
            </div>
        </body>
